metadata.name: Urban Flora #190
metadata.description:
Urban Flora is a generative artwork exploring interplay of natural and artificial forms created by Marcin Ignac / @marcinignac

http://marcinignac.com/projects/urban-flora/

The project was inspired by the 3/4/5G network infrastructure more and more present in the parks and greenery of our cities. Final Urban Flora transformed into a study of abandoned structures of a long forgotten civilisation.

The whole image is generative and/or procedural. Leaves are parametric, twigs and trees use the space colonisation algorithm, and the geometry is based on platonic solids transformed though series of operations.

Features determined at the time of minting:
- one of the platonic solids or a prism
- one of 15 geometry transformations
- a color theme
- leaves or detailed twigs
- leaf's spread and the amount of ridges

'g' / 'tree finger tap' - resolution and export
'drag' - rotate
'scroll' - zoom (on desktop)

Please note the project needs a decent GPU.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

--
With dedication to my wife.

metadata.name: Glossolalia #146
metadata.description:
This series is ultimately about catharsis. The compositions can be chaotic and maybe even a little messy, but they also can be vibrant and diverse… which is really what this is trying to celebrate: diversity and expression.

Simply, it’s about the emotions associated with whatever frees you.

Please see the linked fxtext article (on the main project page) for a more in-depth dissection of the concept. It’s less of a technical discussion, and more about the experience of the artist, and how it became linked with the feelings they associate with the art.

In live mode:

For higher resolutions, you can append “&density=2” to the url to double the size, “&density=3” to triple, and so on.
(This is highly recommended.)

To adjust grain, you can append “&grain=##” to the url. 40 is the default, and 0 will remove it completely.

metadata.name: Azulejo #24
metadata.description:
Azulejo is a generative work made with p5.js

Behind this artwork, the author (eduxdux) had made a lot of research about tiling, the main references for this work were Athos Bulcão, Alexandre Mancini, and "Azulejo da igrejinha" by Cândido Portinari.

This artwork has 8 color palettes and 7 tile styles.
If you have lucky you can have a fully filled tile.

This work is participating in the FxHash anniversary event (#fxhashturnsone) and 10% of the royalties go to the Save Pakistan

Eduxdux November 2022

Ancient generative patterns.

Press 's' or double click/tap to save a PNG
To save 2x, 4x, or 8x versions, press the '2', '3', '4' keys respectively.

Made with thi.ng.
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Backyard #81
metadata.description:
The house I lived in when I was young was a house with a small backyard with brick walls. I often imagined it in the backyard at the time.
If I grow up and have my own house later, I want to live in a house with a backyard with a dense nature and a view of a vast mountain.
Although I haven't achieved the imagination that I did when I was young yet. I'm so happy because I think it came true in the world of generative art.
I hope you have the backyard that you imagine.

--

Features:
 - Canvas: vertical / horizontal
 - Palette: black / red / green / purple / yellow / blue
 - Highlighted object: tree / flowers / brickwall
 - MountainType: standard / sharp
 - Tree: true / false
 - Flowers: true / false
 - Stars: true / false
 - Fog: true / false
 - Brickwall: true / false
 - Sun or Moon: true / false / supersize
 - After the rain: true / false

--

Press "s" in live mode to download the rendered image as a png file. (2000 x 3000 for vertical, 3000 x 1500 for horizontal)

Made with p5js and passion
By thion, September 2023

metadata.name: Luft #17
metadata.description:
"Luft" is my latest interpretation of one of my favorite generative art patterns, Truchet tiles. Meticulously designed tiles are rotated and placed on a grid to create unexpected compositions.

metadata.name: DOS DELIGHT: PIXELS #47
metadata.description:
As a child who encountered computers in the nostalgic era of the 90s, 'Dos Delight' stands as one of my most intimate generative art projects, bridging the gap between my early childhood and the vivid memories intertwined with the world of computing.

In this generative art i am to create aesthetics of 90s computers, tapping into the nostalgia of a bygone era. The algorithm, inspired by the playfulness of childhood, creates whimsical, childish paintings reminiscent of a time when computers were new and learning happened through wild exploration.

Designed to mimic the uninhibited creativity of a child at play, the algorithm produces artworks with pixelated charm, vibrant colors, and blocky shapes.This generative art project becomes a nostalgic time capsule, rekindling the joy of learning through play in the digital landscape of childhood.

Press 4 or 8 to export in 4k and 8k in PNG.
Press 's' to to export in screen resolution.

Murat Atimtay 2024 | @atimtay | https://www.atimtay.xyz

metadata.name: Timing #263
metadata.description:
Time.. 
While one thing happens one time, another happens several times.

----------------------------------------------------------------
  Keys control:
    r: toggle rotation
    i: increment rotation speed
    d: decrement rotation speed
    p: toggle show points
    s: save current size image to .png
    x + 2/4/8: save 2x/4x/8x size image to .png
    1-9 + g: save 1-9 sec animation to .gif (depends on the machine resources)

  URL parameters:
    fps=<value>: frame rate
    r=true: rotation ON
    p=false: do not show points 

---------------------------------------------------------------
    Created with p5.js
    License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0
